        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The change is as in verse 3. What Josiah desired was not only to carry out on this occasion the prescription of the Law, but so to establish the observance that it should continue and not be lightly modified. There is no mention of the passover held in the nineteenth year and in the succeeding years of Josiah’s reign. It would be rash, however, to conclude from such absence of the record, that the same solemnity was not used every succeeding year of the king’s reign, almost as rash as to decide that the passover had been unobserved since the time of Samuel.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The ordinances for putting down them that had familiar spirits and other like superstitions are found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 19:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 20:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 20:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 24.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Moreover the workers with familiar spirits, and the wizards.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Persons of these classes had been encouraged by Manasseh, in his earlier reign (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 21:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and probably by Amon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 21:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). As Josiah designed a thorough reformation, it was necessary for him to put them down. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And the images",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the teraphim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which are thought to have been small images kept as household gods in many Israelite families from a very ancient date (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 31:19-35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The superstition was exceedingly persistent. We find it under the judges (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 18:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), under Saul (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 19:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), here under the later kings, and it is still mentioned after the return from the Captivity (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Zechariah 10:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The superstition was, apparently, Babylonian (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 21:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and brought from Ur of the Chaldees by the family of Abraham. Besides being regarded as household gods, the teraphim were used in divination. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And the idols, and all the abominations that were spied.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The \"idols,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "gillulim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", are probably, like the teraphim, of a private nature, figures used as amulets or talismans. Excepting in Ezekiel, the word is an uncommon one. By the \"abominations that were spied\" are meant secret defilements and superstitious practices in households, which needed to be searched out. (So Thenius and Bahr.) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "In the land of Judah and in Jerusalem.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Not, apparently, in the cities of Samaria, where such a rigid inquisition would perhaps have provoked a stubborn resistance. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Did Josiah put away, that he might perform the words of the Law",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "that he might establish the words of the Law",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Laws against such practices as Josiah now put down will be found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 22:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 19:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 20:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 18:10-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Which were written in the book that Hilkiah the priest found in the house of the Lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 22:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). 2 Kings 23:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Conclusion of Josiah's reign. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". As Josiah had the passover kept in perfect accordance with the precepts of the law, so did he also exterminate the necromancers, the teraphim and all the abominations of idolatry, throughout all Judah and Jerusalem, to set up the words of the law in the book of the law that had been found, i.e., to carry them out and bring them into force. For האבות and היּדּענים see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 21:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". תּרפים, penates, domestic gods, which were worshipped as the authors of earthly prosperity and as oracular deities (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 31:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). גּלּלים and שׁקּצים, connected together, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 29:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as a contemptuous description of idols in general. - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the account of the efforts made by Josiah to restore the true worship of Jehovah closes with a general verdict concerning his true piety. See the remarks on this point at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 18:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". He turned to Jehovah with all his heart, etc.: there is an evident allusion here to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 6:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Compare with this the sentence of the prophet Jeremiah concerning his reign (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 22:15-16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]